  "text": "Clearly, however, the degree to which a given finding in the right eye predicts the probability of the same finding in the left eye varies considerably for diVerent conditions. Some conditions characteristically only ever occur in one eye. This may be because the disease is rare. An example of this is choroidal melanoma which occurs in only one eye in 99% of cases. [CITATION_1] Other examples are corneal herpes simplex infection in the immunocompetent or severe ocular trauma (98% cases 2 ). At the other extreme are conditions such as blepharitis which almost always aVect both eyes (proportion bilateral 95%",
